{"id":"2211.04865","submitter":"Gauthier Rousseau","authors":"Gauthier Rousseau, Thibaut M\\'etivet, Hugo Rousseau, Gilles Daviet,\n  Florence Bertails-Descoubes","title":"Revisiting the role of friction coefficients in granular collapses:\n  confrontation of 3D non-smooth simulations with experiments","comments":"25 figures and 6 movies","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.comp-ph physics.geo-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, transient granular flows are examined both numerically and\nexperimentally. Simulations are performed using the continuous 3D granular\nmodel introduced in Daviet & Bertails-Descoubes (2016), which represents the\ngranular medium as an inelastic and dilatable continuum subject to the\nDrucker-Prager yield criterion in the dense regime. One notable feature of this\nnumerical model is to resolve such a non-smooth rheology without any\nregularisation.\n  We show that this non-smooth model, which relies on a constant friction\ncoefficient, is able to reproduce with high fidelity various experimental\ngranular collapses over inclined erodible beds, provided the friction\ncoefficient is set to the avalanche angle - and not to the stop angle, as\ngenerally done.\n  To better characterise the range of validity of the fully plastic rheology in\ntransient frictional flows, we further revisit established scaling laws\nregarding the shape of the final collapse deposit, and accurately recover the\nexpected power-law dependences.\n  The influence of side wall friction is then investigated using experimental\nand simulated collapses with a varying channel width. The analysis provides a\ncomprehensive framework to estimate the effective flow thickness in relation to\nthe channel width and initial pile height and invalidates assumptions on the\neffective flow thickness formerly made in the literature.\n  Finally, we extend the constant coefficient mode