{"id":"2211.04934","submitter":"Neelesh Kumar Shukla","authors":"Neelesh K Shukla, Msp Raja, Raghu Katikeri, Amit Vaid","title":"DoSA : A System to Accelerate Annotations on Business Documents with\n  Human-in-the-Loop","comments":"Accepted at DaSH@EMNLP2022, 5 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CL","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Business documents come in a variety of structures, formats and information\nneeds which makes information extraction a challenging task. Due to these\nvariations, having a document generic model which can work well across all\ntypes of documents and for all the use cases seems far-fetched. For\ndocument-specific models, we would need customized document-specific labels. We\nintroduce DoSA (Document Specific Automated Annotations), which helps\nannotators in generating initial annotations automatically using our novel\nbootstrap approach by leveraging document generic datasets and models. These\ninitial annotations can further be reviewed by a human for correctness. An\ninitial document-specific model can be trained and its inference can be used as\nfeedback for generating more automated annotations. These automated annotations\ncan be reviewed by human-in-the-loop for the correctness and a new improved\nmodel can be trained using the current model as pre-trained model before going\nfor the next iteration. In this paper, our scope is limited to Form like\ndocuments due to limited availability of generic annotated datasets, but this\nidea can be extended to a variety of other documents as more datasets are\nbuilt. An open-source ready-to-use implementation is made available on GitHub\nhttps://github.com/neeleshkshukla/DoSA.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Nov 2022 15:04:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-10"}
{"id":"2211.04935","submitter":"Benjamin Bugeat","authors":"B. Bugeat, P. C. Boldini, A. M. Hasan, R. Pecnik","title":"Instability in strongly stratified plane Couette flow, with application\n  to supercritical fluids","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper addresses the stability of plane Couette flow in presence of\nstrong density and viscosity stratifications. It is shown that a generalised\ninflection point satisfying the generalised Fjortoft's criterion of instability\nexists when a minimum of kinematic viscosity is present in the base flow. The\nassociated instability is examined for fluids featuring different density and\nviscosity laws. In particular, a supercritical fluid is considered in order to\nshed light on the new unstable mode found by Ren et al. (2019) in such fluids.\nAll the fluids considered feature a minimum of kinematic viscosity at a given\ntemperature. Their inviscid stability in plane Couette flow, whose walls are\ndifferentially heated, is numerically assessed. A simple analytical stability\nmodel introduced by Rayleigh is generalised to stratified flows. It is based on\nthe assumption that the instability is driven by the existence, in the base\nflow profile, of a localised layer containing an excess of $\\Phi$, the\ndensity-weighted vorticity. We show that this layer is associated with the\ncharacteristic scales of the minimum of kinematic viscosity in the flow. This\nmodel is able to reproduce the behaviour of long waves, thereby offering good\npredictions of the stability diagram for all types of stratification. It also\nprovides further physical insights regarding the driving parameters of the\ninstability and stabilising effects. The mechanism of the instability is\nfinally interpreted in terms of shear and inertial baroclinic effects. The\nexistence of the instability in different fluids and flows (e.g. miscible\nfluids) is finally discussed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Nov 2022 15:04:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-10"}
